Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgzuNmmpCpS-pWbDRcZ4AaABAg,,@RenfrewPrume,"Thank you for a beautiful reaction. Many people, including me, consider this one of the greatest movies of all time, perfect in every aspect. It’s certainly the greatest film about the selfless sacrifice of love for the sake of that love. My favorite scene is rarely talked about: the Bulgarian woman’s story. It is cleverly written to avoid the Hays Office censors, while remaining convincingly natural. Joy Page, just out of high school at age 17, acted it magnificently. Unfortunately, her acting career was stunted, rather than helped, by her stepfather, studio head Jack Warner.

Bogart and Bergman are icons of classic Hollywood. Both won Oscars, Bogart for “The African Queen” (1951) and Bergman for “Gaslight” (1944). As an old guy (nearly 72), I am always delighted to see a young reactor fall in love with the movies I grew up watching on TV. Bogart made many outstanding films. Others especially recommended are “The Treasure of the Sierra Madre” (1948) and “The Maltese Falcon” (1941).",2026-05-01T23:25:31Z,2026-05-01T23:25:31Z,1,False,0.0,2026-05-02T02:01:02.697979
