Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgzXvxBIaTe8MOIPfIl4AaABAg,,@p-51d95,"Something that’s interesting is both the time that movie was set and also what was happening when the film was actually released. 

From the dialog the film is set after WW2 started in Europe in Sept 1939 and just before the US entered the war in Dec 7, 1941 (Rick: ""If it's December 1941 in Casablanca, what time is it in New York?… I'd bet they're asleep in New York. I'd bet they're asleep all over America”). And film is set in French Morocco, part of unoccupied Vichy France which was the (nominal) ally of Germany at the time but still a sovereign country (hence, the reason the Germans could not just arrest Victor Laszlo). 

The film came out on November 26, 1942 after the US entry into the war. And Operation Torch, the invasion of Vichy French Morocco by the allies, had just occurred on November 8, 1942 and had succeeded by November 16. So, can you imagine the reaction of those people watching the movie when it first came out, 10 days later. And remember it was still not certain who would win the war at that point. Not only is it a great movie but its release had impeccable timing.",2026-05-01T21:01:27Z,2026-05-01T21:07:19Z,18,False,0.0,2026-05-02T02:01:02.698120
